data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET Core+. This is the biggest pitfall.
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` is also removed** — no equivalent exists.
3. The idiomatic replacement is `CancellationToken` + `Task` with cooperative cancellation.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes work with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate MUST observe the CancellationToken for reliable cancellation.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block until completion or timeout. Task.Wait throws
            // AggregateException on fault or cancellation.
            task.Wait(CancellationToken.None);
        }
        catch (AggregateException ae) when (ae.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            var inner = ae.InnerException!;

            if (inner is OperationCanceledException && cts.IsCancellationRequested)
                throw new TimeoutException(
                    $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout", inner);

            throw inner; // Preserve original exception for non-timeout faults
        }

        return task.Result;
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Async overload — preferred in modern .NET code.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Drop-in for legacy callers that can't pass a CancellationToken.
    /// ⚠️ WARNING: Cannot forcibly terminate uncooperative work — it will
    /// continue running in the background until it finishes naturally.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            if (task.Wait(timeout))
                return task.Result;
        }
        catch (AggregateException ae) when (ae.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw ae.InnerException!;
        }

        // Cancel the token (signals cooperative listeners, if any)
        cts.Cancel();

        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No forced termination** | Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, there is **no way** to forcibly kill a running `Task` in .NET 8. Work must check `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` or `token.IsCancellationRequested` at safe points. |
| **Fire-and-forget leaks** | The legacy overload abandons the task on timeout — it keeps running, holding resources. The old code killed the thread; the new code cannot. |
| **`Task.Wait` vs `await`** | `Task.Wait()` blocks the calling thread and wraps exceptions in `AggregateException`. Prefer the async overload. |
| **`WaitAsync` (.NET 6+)** | `Task.WaitAsync(CancellationToken)` is the modern way to apply timeouts to tasks you don't control. |
| **Signature change** | The preferred overload now takes `Func<CancellationToken, T>` instead of `Func<T>` — callers must be updated. |

### Caller Migration Example

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SlowDatabaseQuery(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — preferred, cooperative cancellation
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => SlowDatabaseQuery(ct), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — async preferred
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
    ct => SlowDatabaseQueryAsync(ct), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

**Bottom line:** The old pattern relied on `Thread.Abort()` for preemptive cancellation, which was always dangerous (corrupted state, leaked locks). .NET 8 forces cooperative cancellation via `CancellationToken` — safer, but requires downstream code to participate.
